column5: {50106: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50106",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt by the Responder tool to perform an Adversary-in-the-Middle attack by poisoning the SMB protocol and intercepting traffic between devices on the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {20158: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "20158",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to log in to the Oracle GlassFish Server using the default administrative credentials (username \\\'admin\\\' and password \\\'adminadmin\\\'), which is an example of abusing a valid account for initial access or privilege escalation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "20158", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule specifically looks for the default credentials, it could also be indicative of a brute force attack attempt against the Oracle GlassFish Server\\\'s login mechanism."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {10088: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10088",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a keylogger named \\\'Beyond Keylogger\\\' attempting to exfiltrate captured data over SMTP, which could be considered a command and control channel for this malware."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "10088", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions \\\'Beyond Keylogger\\\', which is a type of malware that captures user input like keystrokes to steal sensitive information like credentials."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {24087: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "24087",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1572",\\n    "Technique name": "Protocol Tunneling",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may tunnel network communications to and from a victim system within a separate protocol to avoid detection/network filtering and/or enable access to otherwise unreachable systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a known Trojan (Bledoor) that tunnels TCP traffic over UDP to bypass network filtering and detection mechanisms. The rule looks for specific byte patterns in the UDP payload that indicate the presence of an encapsulated TCP header, which is a common technique used for protocol tunneling."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {26803: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "26803",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1048",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over a different protocol than that of the existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects potential data exfiltration attempts over the DNS protocol, which is an alternative protocol to the typical command and control channel. column5: {21318: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21318",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a known Trojan malware variant (Win.Trojan.FakeAV TDSS/PurpleHaze) that uses the application layer protocol HTTP to communicate with its command and control server, likely to blend in with normal web traffic and evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "21318", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1132",\\n    "Technique name": "Data Encoding",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may encode data to make the content of command and control traffic more difficult to detect\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for base64 encoded data in the HTTP request, which suggests the malware is encoding its communications to obfuscate the content and evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {14075: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "14075",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects activity related to the Ultimate Keylogger Pro malware, which is designed to capture user input such as keystrokes and send reports over SMTP (email). column5: {13642: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "13642",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a keylogger malware attempting to exfiltrate captured data over the SMTP protocol, which could be used as a command and control channel for data exfiltration."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "13642", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions detecting a keylogger malware, which is designed to capture user input such as keystrokes to steal sensitive information like credentials."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50467: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50467",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1003",\\n    "Technique name": "OS Credential Dumping",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to dump credentials to obtain account login and credential material, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system and software"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to use the Mimikatz tool, which is commonly used for credential dumping on Windows systems. The rule looks for specific content related to the Mimikatz tool being transferred over SMB (port 445), indicating an attempt to dump credentials from the operating system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50467", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1550",\\n    "Technique name": "Use Alternate Authentication Material",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use alternate authentication material, such as password hashes, Kerberos tickets, and application access tokens, in order to move laterally within an environment and bypass normal system access controls"],\\n    "Explanation": "Mimikatz is a tool that can be used to obtain alternate authentication material, such as password hashes or Kerberos tickets, which can then be used for lateral movement and privilege escalation within the compromised environment."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {32804: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32804",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects known malicious JavaScript packers commonly used in exploit kits for drive-by compromise attacks, where malicious code is delivered to a victim\\\'s system when they visit a compromised website."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "32804", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for patterns indicative of obfuscated or packed JavaScript, which could be used to exploit client-side vulnerabilities and execute malicious code on the victim\\\'s system."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {48508: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48508",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP connections from an infected host to external servers, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with normal web traffic and avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "48508", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1102",\\n    "Technique name": "Web Service",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for HTTP requests to external servers with specific URI patterns (/wp-content/plugins/), which could indicate the use of a legitimate web service for command and control by the ZeusPanda malware."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {60297: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60297",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1505",\\n    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to access a PHP web shell named \\\'Cybershell\\\', which is a malicious server software component that can provide persistent remote access and control over the compromised server."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "60297", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1190",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for inbound HTTP requests to a public-facing web server that may be attempting to exploit a vulnerability or access a malicious web shell, which could allow initial access to the network."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {31564: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "31564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects data exfiltration by the CosmicDuke malware over an FTP command and control channel. column5: {37378: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37378",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to log in to an ABB web application using the default password \\\'service:ABB800xA\\\'. column5: {40331: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "40331",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to log in to the JBoss JMX console using the default \\\'admin:admin\\\' credentials, which is an example of abusing a valid account to gain initial access or privilege escalation."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "40331", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained"],\\n    "Explanation": "While the rule specifically looks for the default \\\'admin:admin\\\' credentials, it could also be used as part of a brute force attack where an adversary tries multiple common or default credentials."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44563: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44563",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from the internal network to the internet, which could be an indicator of malware using the application layer protocol (HTTP) for command and control communication, blending in with normal web traffic to evade detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44563", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1090",\\n    "Technique name": "Proxy",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule looks for a specific header (CF-RAY) that is associated with Cloudflare, a popular proxy service. column5: {19079: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19079",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer\\\'s getElementById object, which could allow an attacker to execute arbitrary code on the client system through a drive-by compromise attack."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "19079", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1189",\\n    "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for signs of a drive-by compromise attack, where malicious code is executed on the client system when the user visits a compromised website."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {44564: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "44564",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP traffic from a PowerShell Empire variant, which is a post-exploitation agent that uses the HTTP protocol for command and control communication. column5: {37387: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37387",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1078",\\n    "Technique name": "Valid Accounts",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may obtain and abuse credentials of existing accounts as a means of gaining Initial Access, Persistence, Privilege Escalation, or Defense Evasion"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to log in to a Moxa device using the default \\\'admin:root\\\' credentials, which falls under the \\\'Valid Accounts\\\' technique where adversaries abuse existing account credentials to gain unauthorized access."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "37387", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1110",\\n    "Technique name": "Brute Force",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use brute force techniques to gain access to accounts when passwords are unknown or when password hashes are obtained"],\\n    "Explanation": "While not explicitly stated, this rule could also be triggered by brute force attempts using the default \\\'admin:root\\\' credentials, which aligns with the \\\'Brute Force\\\' technique where adversaries attempt to guess credentials."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {4917: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "4917",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Microsoft Internet Explorer\\\'s JavaScript engine, which could allow an adversary to execute arbitrary code on the client system by obfuscating malicious JavaScript code within the onLoad event handler of a web page."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "4917", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1027",\\n    "Technique name": "Obfuscated Files or Information",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule specifically looks for obfuscated JavaScript code that attempts to exploit the vulnerability, which aligns with the Obfuscated Files or Information technique used by adversaries to evade detection."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {4060: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "4060",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1021",\\n    "Technique name": "Remote Services",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use Valid Accounts to log into a service that accepts remote connections, such as telnet, SSH, and VNC"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempted connection to the Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) service on port 3389, specifically targeting the Administrator account. column5: {47900: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47900",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule detects outbound HTTP connections from an infected host to an external server, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate using the application layer protocol HTTP to blend in with normal traffic and avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47900", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1008",\\n    "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule appears to be detecting a variant of the OilRig malware, which is known to use fallback channels for command and control communication in case the primary channel is unavailable."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {58814: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "58814",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1608",\\n    "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects attempts to download Java class files, which could be used to stage malicious capabilities on the target system. column5: {7159: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "7159",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1056",\\n    "Technique name": "Input Capture",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information"],\\n    "Explanation": "This Snort rule detects activity related to the Win-Spy keylogger, which is designed to capture user input such as keystrokes to steal sensitive information like credentials. column5: {33942: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33942",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects the download of executable control panel (.cpl) files, which could be used by an adversary to transfer malicious tools or payloads into the target environment."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "33942", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1036",\\n    "Technique name": "Masquerading",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule excludes specific legitimate .cpl files, suggesting that adversaries may attempt to masquerade their malicious payloads as legitimate control panel files."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {38565: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38565",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1197",\\n    "Technique name": "BITS Jobs",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may abuse BITS jobs to persistently execute code and perform various background tasks\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects a Trojan (Win.Trojan.Sweeper) attempting to download a malicious file using the BITS (Background Intelligent Transfer Service) protocol, which is commonly abused by malware to execute code and perform tasks in the background."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "38565", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1105",\\n    "Technique name": "Ingress Tool Transfer",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may transfer tools or other files from an external system into a compromised environment\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for an initial download attempt of a malicious binary file (.bin) from an external source, which aligns with the Ingress Tool Transfer technique where adversaries transfer tools or files into a compromised environment."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {52621: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "52621",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1203",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Client Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in client applications to execute code"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a vulnerability in Apple Safari\\\'s WebKit engine that allows for arbitrary code execution via user-assisted AppleScript. The rule looks for specific JavaScript code patterns that could be used to trigger the vulnerability and execute malicious code on the client system."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "52621", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1204",\\n    "Technique name": "User Execution",\\n    "Quotes": ["An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule mentions \\\'user assisted\\\' in the description, indicating that some user interaction is required to trigger the exploit, aligning with the User Execution technique where an adversary relies on user actions to gain code execution."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {56862: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1071",\\n    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects outbound HTTP POST requests from an infected host to an external server, which could be an attempt by malware to communicate with a command and control server using the application layer protocol HTTP. This aligns with the T1071 technique where adversaries use application layer protocols like HTTP to blend in with normal network traffic and avoid detection."\\n  },\\n  {\\n    "sid": "56862", \\n    "Technique ID": "T1041",\\n    "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",\\n    "Quotes": ["\\\'Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\\\'"],\\n    "Explanation": "The rule is looking for outbound HTTP POST requests with specific content, which could indicate an attempt by malware to exfiltrate data over the command and control channel it establishes. This matches the T1041 technique where adversaries exfiltrate data over the same channel used for command and control communications."\\n  }\\n]\', type=\'text\')]'}

column5: {50104: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "50104",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1557",\\n    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt by the Responder tool to perform an Adversary-in-the-Middle attack by poisoning the SMB negotiation process. column5: {47461: '[TextBlock(text=\'[\\n  {\\n    "sid": "47461",\\n    "Technique ID": "T1068",\\n    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Privilege Escalation",\\n    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may exploit software vulnerabilities in an attempt to elevate privileges"],\\n    "Explanation": "This rule detects an attempt to exploit a privilege escalation vulnerability in the CTSWebProxy ActiveX control.
